    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#boardman1966"/>, p. <citedRange>155</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#cdl1970"/>, p. <citedRange>251, b</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>000300</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><orig>πβ</orig>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>Intraduisible.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Intraducibile.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمه بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
	       <p>The main interest of those letters is the shape of beta, which is typically Theran and might have been scratched before the other graffito 
	           appended on the same dish, see <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr000500</ref>.</p>
	       <p>The right vertical stroke of pi is so short that it might perhaps be a gamma, unfortunately resulting in no better reading.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
